o identify conservation strategies with partners this is also an exercise to identify ecologically important corridors and or barriers that impact connectivity not to plan for new designated lands the first twoday workshop was held in may 2008 presentations included a summary of the project goals a review of basic landscape ecology principles an introduction to potential modeling methods that could be employed an overview of uncertainty and available data layers a summary of potential conservation partnerships important discussion points included exploration of how to incorporate climate change into modeling efforts how to define land cover and or ecosystem categories how to select an appropriate scale of analysis whether to focus attention on individual species species groups or biomes ecosystems at the conclusion of the first workshop all agreed that this project is a relevant and timely first step in addressing the impacts of climate change in alaska however because of uncertainty about the outcomes of various methods for modeling corridors and the accuracy and resolution of currently modeled biome shifts we have decided to approach the problem more incrementally in the interim between the first and second workshops falk huettman will develop a more alaskaspecific model of vegetation and biome change over the next 100 years and use these layers in corridor modeling for important but disparate single species caribou blueberry trumpeter swan and alaska marmot our collective evaluation of the outcomes of these pilot efforts at our second workshop will help us to refine the goal s and modeling approach es for the final product for more information contact dr nancy fresco  9074742405 attachment size connecting alaska landscapes into the future 1742 mb united states fish and wildlife service university of alaska fairbanks ',0),(84,'node',' usgs land cover change the us geological survey and snap are working together to predict generalized changes in land cover over time and relate those changes to habitat suitability indices for specific key trust species within selected doi lands in alaska specific tasks include using snap data and downscaling procedures to identify the types of relevant quantitative and qualitative information needed for predicting land cover change investigate appropriate model or models to use help in the selection of a pilot area for initial products for more information contact dr nancy fresco  9074742405 united states geological survey ',0),(85,'node',' yukon water availability analysis the highlatitude ecosystems of the yukon are vulnerable to climate change including hydrologic changes to predict potential changes in growing season water balance in the yukon snap and yukon college collaborated to develop a modeling tool for mapping future growingseason water availability the model focused on estimating the growingseason balance between precipitation p and potential evapotranspiration pet a term used to describe the likely amount of water that could be returned to the atmosphere through the combination of evaporation and transpiration results showed that much of the yukon is likely to remain waterlimited during summer months with the balance between p and pet remaining negative subtle changes were predicted in this balance with some regional drying particularly in the boreal regions however the greatest impacts to ecosystem hydrology may stem from associated climatedriven changes such as increases in growing season length and growing degree days and associated vegetation shifts changing drainage from permafrost loss and altered fire cycles for more information contact dr nancy fresco  9074742405 attachment size final report 114 mb yukon college ',0),(86,'node',' expertise ',0),(87,'node',' who we are ',0),(88,'node',' climate scenario planning as a community our most pressing issue is not how to resolve the remaining uncertainties in climate science but rather how to make sound decisions based on the information we do have   climate policy initiative snap offers data and analysis in two flavors quantitative  standard scientific language such as ranges of temperature projections with error values representing the standard deviation between models  qualitative  narrative scenarios that explore what if questions using models and other information to describe several possible futures the most applicable scenarios fall within the range of reasonable possibility and challenge leaders and managers to come up with strategies flexible enough to address each possibility how representative concentration pathways fit into scenario planning snap uses scenario planning to make useful decisions despite uncertainties in data analysis and interpretation representative concentration pathways  rcps are the latest phase in the scenario development process these are  pathways of future radiative forcings changes in balance between concentrations of radiation caused by changes in gases such as co2 and representative  of the current literature the 4 rcps include a mitigation scenario leading to a very low forcing level in 2100 rcp26 two medium stabilization scenarios in 2100 rcp45 and rcp6 a very high baseline emission scenario in 2100 rcp85 rcps are not a complete package of socioeconomic emissions and climate projections rcps do not represent specific futures regarding climate policy action or no action each rcp is consistent with many scenarios because different socioeconomic futures could give rise to similar changes in atmospheric composition using rcps in scenario planning provides a common starting point for scenario planning and adds value to the work we do for clients  scenario planning scenario planning scenario planning scenario planning climate scenario planning  ',1400624818),(89,'node',' collaboration climate change planning encompasses atmospheric and geophysical sciences biological sciences and social sciences weighing choices often requires expertise in economics or knowl